metadata.name: Sketch D #8
metadata.description:
Sketch is an open-ended series. Works evolve as I code a generative project, sometimes drastically. Intermediate works usually don't see the light of day - they get archived and forgotten. This series is snapshots of different forms along the way - each standing alone, but also part of a larger meandering work flow. The word Sketch implies incompleteness. This project may end up being two works, or it could evolve for years. Part of the joy of generative art is never knowing what's around the corner. I have no set schedule. There may be multiple Sketches released a week, or it could be weeks or months between drops. I have no idea where Sketch is heading and there is no guarantee of cohesiveness from Sketch to Sketch. Color palettes and forms will change as new ideas are explored.

Sketch D (Disruption). The grid is broken. The color palette from Sketches A, B, and C remains. Most outputs are simply single colors or black and white. Grid size, padding, and colors vary.

Press the spacebar to see the unDisturbed structure.

metadata.name: Lovehate #36
metadata.description:
1240 random words are generated from the Love an Hate characters. When, by chance, these words are formed, they are marked with a circle and joined by lines. The word combinations are formed until two Loves or two Hates, or one of each, or up to a number that can be greater than 8 Loves and Hates and their respective graph of extreme feelings appear.

You can save an 8000x8000px image by clicking on "open" and typing J for jpg or P for png.

Made in P5js by Diego de los Campos under NFT License 2.0
10% goes to the wonderful Processing Foundation!

metadata.name: Bonsai Bonanza #707
metadata.description:
In previous works, I was attracted by the idea of ​​the domestication of plants.
According to Wikipedia, the purposes of bonsai are primarily contemplation for the viewer, and the pleasant exercise of effort and ingenuity for the grower. By contrast with other plant cultivation practices, bonsai is not intended for production of food or for medicine. Instead, bonsai practice focuses on long-term cultivation and shaping of one or more small trees growing in a container.
I pressume that the main intention is aesthetic. The beauty. Because we love beautiful things.
It is very interesting how we modify certain creatures for our sake of satisfaction.

May this collection brings you good fortune.

metadata.name: <iframes> #138
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: Nowhere Stamps #6
metadata.description:
Is it possible to find geographic coordinates or names of the places where the artistic experiment leads us? Does the journey called research have an end point?

We are trying to track it via postage stamps for envelopes coming from there.

Thanks for the aesthetic inspiration to Sigmar Polke, who lived and studied at the Düsseldorf Arts Academy, not far from our current place of living.
His works were called a European Pop art, because of translating everyday life into enigmatic narratives.
Experimenting with materials and chemicals, mixing together traditional pigments with varnishes, toxins and resins to produce spontaneous chemical reactions, he was making art created by chance. He combined analog alchemy with tinting and altering methods on a computer.

In our case, alchemy is the images, produced by the neural networks, the results of which cannot be predicted. One can only guess, try to ask them the right question.

Chemistry and pigments are p5.js tools that also sometimes spontaneously produce unpredictable results.

The process of creating ‘Nowhere Stamps’ became a great journey and adventure in itself.

Work is made in collaboration with artist, musician and poet Yulikolay.
